This is the "rapidcow/fresh" tap for the Homebrew package manager.
This was going on Codeberg, but because stuff is partially written
by Claude [*] (solely to fight my procrastiation & perfectionism,
and not a reflection of... y'know... my endorsement of the "hype"
around all this), I am hosting it myself, mirroring it on GitHub
secondly, and probably delete it from Codeberg to keep my account
AI-clean there...

I am trying to learn Ruby as well, to see how similar to Perl it is.
GitHub[1], Homebrew, Mastodon all run on Ruby, so it is interesting
to say the least.

To add this tap, the third <URL> argument is often necessary:

    brew tap rapidcow/fresh    # Embrace GitHub
    brew tap rapidcow/fresh \
          https://codeberg.org/rapidcow/homebrew-fresh.git
                               # Pray that Codeberg doesn't boot me
                               # for including AI-generated code
    brew tap rapidcow/fresh \
          https://git.rapidcow.org/pub/package/homebrew/fresh.git
                               # ... or me? :p

To remove it (or to re-add it later with a different URL):

    brew untap rapidcow/fresh

[1] This is purely speculating from Scott Chacon's Pro Git book,
    which utilizes Ruby to demonstrate zlib compression used in
    Git loose objects:
    <https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Git-Internals-Git-Objects#_object_storage>

[*] Anything authored by AI has explicit attribution, by the way.
Generally the way Claude Code works is append the Co-Authored-By
header, and still have git log, git blame, etc. show my name.
I don't do that, because it messes with my brain if I see myself
authoring more code than I should be capable of writing!  Instead
I give Claude the full "author"-ship and I as the committer, so
I'd still know who to "blame" for anything off-putting.  None of
this is because of standards-conformity or transparency... I'm
doing this for *myself* primarily and I just thought it might be
worth saying.
